  "prompt": "Is money laundering a crime?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is a crime in virtually every country around the world. It involves the process of making illegally obtained money (often referred to as \"dirty money\") appear legitimate (or \"clean\") by disguising its true origin. This typically involves three stages:\n\n1. **Placement**: Introducing the illegal funds into the financial system.\n2. **Layering**: Concealing the source of the money through complex transactions and bookkeeping.\n3. **Integration**: Making the money appear legitimate by integrating it into the economy, such as through investments or business operations.\n\nMoney laundering is illegal because it enables criminals to profit from illegal activities (such as drug trafficking, fraud, corruption, and terrorism) without detection by law enforcement. It also undermines the integrity of financial systems and economies.\n\n### Legal Consequences\nThe penalties for money laundering can be severe, including:\n- Significant fines\n- Imprisonment\n- Asset forfeiture (seizure of assets believed to be involved in or obtained through laundering)\n- Damage to personal and professional reputation\n\nInternational organizations like the **Financial Action Task Force (FATF)** work to combat money laundering globally by setting standards and promoting effective implementation of anti-money laundering (AML) measures. Many countries have also established their own laws and regulatory bodies to detect and prevent money laundering.",
